<TEXT>
iraq announced monday it had carried out a plan to move western 
hostages to vital military installations to deter any us attack 
and warned its people not to try to hide any of the thousands of 
foreigners trapped in the country 
with the united state building up its armed forces in saudi 
arabia and blocking iraqi ports with an armada of ships the iraqi 
regime moved to use the westerners as human shields 
for the first time president bush publicly referred to the 
3000 americans and the other western captives as hostages 
whatever these innocent people are called they are in fact 
hostages he said in baltimore he demanded their release 
in a blow to iraqi president saddam hussein iran announced 
monday that it will abide by a un resolution ordering economic 
sanctions against iraq this followed saddams moves last week to 
make peace with iran his longtime enemy so as to better focus on 
his confrontation with the west 
late monday the un security council met informally to pursue 
possible un action to enforce its embargo of iraq diplomats 
entering the meeting carried draft papers that called for members 
to use all necessary action to enforce the embargo 
the meeting occurred as an iraqi tanker one of two tankers 
fired on saturday by us ships was reported about to enter yemeni 
waters 
the official iraqi news agency quoted a spokesman for baghdads 
national council or parliament as saying iraqs foreign guests 
have been in fact moved to all vital and military installations 
they have been provided with all modern facilities and they are all 
in good physical condition 
it did not say how many foreigners were moved or give other 
details 
in washington the state department reported that 1214 
americans and some other foreigners were taken from their kuwait 
hotels and moved to undisclosed locations a us official said the 
americans included both men and women adding they may be going 
to baghdad 
earlier monday saddams government informed diplomats they had 
until friday to close their missions in kuwait or lose their 
special status 
several countries said they had no plans to close their 
embassies they included austria britain denmark finland 
france italy spain sweden the soviet union and west germany 
in other developments monday 
israel said it will allow egyptians fleeing iraq and kuwait to 
travel through the jewish state on their way home israeli tv said 
a us embassy spokesman said in amman that american citizens 
in jordan were being advised to leave on a voluntary basis 
an nbc newswall street journal poll conducted over the weekend 
found that 72 percent of those surveyed approved of how bush is 
handling the crisis seventy percent said they approve of the 
decision to send military forces to saudi arabia and the gulf the 
telephone poll had a margin of error of four percent nbc said 
janes defense weekly in london reported that an iraqi 
freighter is heading to jordan with 17 east germanmade armored 
bridgelayers the bridgelayers are capable of crossing difficult 
terrain because it has a 66footlong scissorlike bridge iraq 
received seven last year in an earlier deal the magazine said 
amnesty international demanded the immediate release of all 
foreigners detained in iraq and kuwait and protested reported 
human rights abuses by iraqi troops in kuwait 
american military cargo planes are being allowed to operate 
from the united arab emirates becoming the second gulf nation to 
accept foreign troops in response to the iraq crisis defense 
secretary dick cheney said 
in new york wholesale unleaded gasoline prices surged over the 
1 mark for the first time boosted by the belief among traders 
that the mideast crisis will persist and continue creating tight 
supplies 
in hampton va 20 f117a stealth fighters left langley air 
force base for deployment in the middle east 
col moammar gadhafi criticized both iraq and the united states 
for provocative actions in the mideast and threatened to withdraw 
libya from the united nations 
in warning their own people about harboring foreigners iraqi 
authorities said monday that anyone doing so faced the severest 
punishment according to iraqi radio the report said the rule 
applied to iraqs entire administrative border apparently 
including kuwait 
iraq invaded the small emirate aug 2 after accusing it of 
cheating on opec production quotas thus driving down world oil 
prices and depriving iraq of billions of dollars in revenue iraq 
declared four days later that it had annexed kuwait and began 
referring to it as a city in southern iraq 
two senior un officials went to baghdad to press for release 
of foreigners held in kuwait and iraq secretarygeneral javier 
perez de cuellar said saddam asked that the envoys be sent 
eduard a shevardnadze the soviet foreign minister appealed to 
a visiting iraqi deputy premier in moscow to free the foreigners 
tass said he expressed satisfaction to saadoun hammadi that 
soviet citizens were allowed to leave and asked for a similar 
decision in relation to citizens of other states 
opec said there was not enough support among members to call an 
emergency meeting on saudi arabias request for increased output to 
make up the shortage of 5 million barrels a day caused by the loss 
of iraqi and kuwaiti production 
hisham nazer saudi arabias oil minister said saturday his 
country would increase production by up to 2 million barrels a day 
with or without support from the organization of petroleum 
exporting countries 
ship radios crackled monday with the sounds of us warships 
challenging nearly every commercial vessel in the southern persian 
gulf but no iraqi vessels were found in the area shipping sources 
reported 
addressing the national veterals of foreign wars convention in 
baltimore bush said 
we have been reluctant to use the term hostage but when 
saddam hussein specifically offers to trade the freedom of those 
citizens of many nations he holds against their will in return for 
concessions there can be little doubt that whatever these innocent 
people are called they are in fact hostages 
and i want there to be no misunderstanding i will hold the 
government of iraq responsible for the safety and wellbeing of 
american citizens being held against their will 
on sunday saddam offered to release foreigners if the united 
states withdrew its forces from the persian gulf region and 
promised to lift the economic embargo us officials refused 
he said later he would free citizens of nations that remained 
neutral in the conflict including those of austria switzerland 
sweden finland and portugal they account for only about 600 of 
the 21000 foreigners in iraq and kuwait 
iraq said monday that indonesian and some argentines would be 
allowed to leave chinas official news agency xinhua said the 
first group of 97 chinese was leaving and tass said 122 soviet 
citizens crossed into jordan on monday 346 had reached the border 
and only 188 remain in kuwait 
foreign minister saud alfaisal of saudi arabia visited damascus 
on monday to discuss the gulf crisis with syrian leaders 
irans official islamic republic news agency said iraqi soldiers 
continued withdrawing from occupied iranian territory freeing 
thousands of troops to face us forces iraq and iran also are 
repatriating prisoners from their eightyear war which ended with 
a ceasefire in august of 1988 
despite their newly established peace however iran informed 
perez de cuellar that as a un member it would go along with the 
sanctions ordered by the world body irna reported 
the united states is pouring military personnel into saudi 
arabia and us officials have said the deployment could reach 
200000 american warships and aircraft carriers are stationed in 
and near the persian gulf 
other western and arab countries have contributed troops to the 
growing multinational force but it is predominantly american 
</TEXT>
