<TEXT>
contra supplier eugene hasenfus and a fellow 
courier killed during a failed mission in nicaragua had no formal 
contract and knew the risks of the covert flight defense attorneys 
said monday during closing arguments 
but lawyers for hasenfus and the family of wallace sawyer jr 
say the men deserve to be taken care of for working on behalf 
of a network approved by the white house to support the contra 
rebels in nicaragua 
jury deliberations were scheduled to begin tuesday in the 
fiveweek civil trial which was severely limited after us 
district judge c clyde atkins threw out a major portion of the 
claims last week 
all that remains to consider are some financial issues such as 
whether hasenfus is due back pay and if sawyers family can collect 
death benefits from gen richard secord and miamibased southern 
air transport 
atkins ruled friday that jurors cannot consider damages for 
mental stress suffered by hasenfus or his wife sally after the 
plane was shot down by sandinista troops in october 1986 hasenfus 
of marinette wis was the sole survivor of the crash he was 
detained for three months before being returned to the united 
states 
the judge also removed from the case claims seeking punitive 
damages and allegations the aircraft was unsafe 
thomas spencer an attorney for secord said his client did not 
have the authority to make a contract with hasenfus or sawyer of 
magnolia ark who went by the nickname buzz 
my client didnt contribute to the death of buzz sawyer or the 
harm to gene hasenfus said spencer the white house called him 
and asked to help with the resupply operation 
southern air attorney robert beckman said the carrier was just 
one of several companies involved flights to supply the usbacked 
contra rebels who were fighting the marxist sandinista government 
of nicaragua 
hasenfus could just as well brought suit against the maker of 
the parachute that saved his life he said 
defense attorney brian strange told the jury hasenfus and his 
wife should at least be reimbursed for expenses connected to 
hasenfus legal battle in nicaragua 
they were told their families would be taken care of and then 
the defense comes before you and says not us said strange 
secord helped former national security council aide oliver north 
organize the contra supply network secord was sentenced to two 
years probation after pleading guilty to lying to congress about 
his role in the irancontra affair 
