<DOCNO> AP900820-0004 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a quiet revolution is under way in dozens 
of rural southern counties where people historically unrepresented 
are nurturing a shadow government to help them take the last step 
up from slavery 
this alternative power structure conceived by a descendant of 
slaves and based on thomas jeffersons ideas is called simply 
the assembly 
it has brought millions of dollars worth of new schools miles 
of paved roads and most important to the assembly members who are 
mostly black a voice that can no longer be ignored 
in appomattox county gospel songfests and candy sales helped 
the local assembly raise 65000 purchase six acres and clear the 
land for a community center 
we were always going from one place to another having our 
meetings said milton chambers the 36yearold assembly 
president a foundry worker who lives three miles from the spot 
where the civil war ended 125 years ago 
to have a building to call our own he said members gladly 
sacrificed some contributing hundreds of dollars 
the only way to control our destiny he said is to be 
able to turn on and cut off the lights when we want to 
in a phrase he was stating the goal and purpose of the 40odd 
assemblies in virginia and other southern states organization for 
selfhelp and representation 
ill say it til i die if you give people something youll 
build dependency said don anderson a black former congressional 
committee lawyer who created the assembly system but if you just 
organize the voluntarism theyll do it themselves 
and once its done its like magic 
for 22 years anderson has been trying to work that magic 
through his washington dcbased national association for the 
southern poor 
with a staff of 10 and an annual budget of nearly 500000 
mostly from individual donors and foundations its goal is to 
create assemblies in 258 southern counties with low incomes and 
black populations of about 30 percent to 80 percent 
anderson has written that his aim was to give these people a 
vehicle for solving their problems and for taking the last step up 
from slavery 
most assemblies are in virginia and north carolina but new ones 
are being formed in georgia and south carolina and plans are to 
expand to alabama mississippi louisiana arkansas and tennessee 
to spread his selfhelp concept across the region anderson 
touts assemblies accomplishments to date the paving of 20 miles 
of roads in black areas of washington county nc job training 
for the hardcore unemployed in portsmouth va 25 million in 
water line extensions and home renovations through federal grants 
in jones county nc and many other projects 
the assemblies operate within a very refined structure based 
on jeffersons idea of ward republics anderson explained 
we go into a county and divide it up into manageable groups of 
50 people each the equivalent of jeffersons wards anderson 
said and these are represented in a central decisionmaking body 
called the assembly 
to establish an assembly andersons organizers usually spend 
two months locating community leaders and bringing them together in 
preliminary meetings anderson who attends a final organizational 
gathering said it costs 18000 on average to organize a county 
procedurally the assembly is a very accurate copy of the 
british house of commons said anderson who holds a degree from 
the london school of economics 
at a recent meeting of the assembly of charlotte county va in 
a muggy school auditorium members who were dressed as if for 
church closely followed parliamentary rules calling questions 
printed on an agenda named the order paper rising whenever 
addressing the group and directing all comments to the speaker 
the difference is that at the house of commons they dont serve 
fried chicken and biscuits beforehand 
assembly members must be at least 18 and must be registered 
voters although the groups are nonpartisan voter registration 
often is a firstpriority project 
the relationship between the assembly and local elected 
officials varies 
i see it as a system to assist the government thats in 
place said andrew murray who heads the assembly in caswell 
county nc 
others see it as a watchdog organization the appomattox 
assembly and others have appointed members to monitor county 
supervisor and school board meetings 
in surry county va three assembly members sit on the 
fivemember county board of supervisors 
so all the issues that come up in the assembly are heard by 
members that can actually vote on them said surry assembly 
president thomas hardy who also chairs the county planning 
commission 
surrys assembly founded 21 years ago is the oldest and most 
successful hardy proudly showed off its projects to a reporter 
some came about through grants the group applied for some through 
its pressure on local officials 
a neat 50unit subsidized apartment complex built after the 
assembly decried the fallingdown tinroofed shacks that many 
lived in is to be expanded 
a 1 million medical clinic put up by the assembly with 
foundation grants has visiting specialists and is working to find 
fulltime doctors 
a handsome 540000 recreation center hums with activity a 
summer day camp program for schoolchildren meetings of senior 
citizens civic group gatherings even wedding receptions 
as everyone benefits from the improvements relations between 
the races have improved hardy said a white official sheriff wc 
andrews agreed 
its a lot of times that maybe we dont see eye to eye the 
sheriff said but we get together and try to work things out 
of all the changes the assembly has brought in surry a farming 
county where pork peanuts and pines are grown hardy is proudest 
of the schools 
before the assembly started its work with a housebyhouse voter 
registration drive that made clear the black majority the schools 
were in a desperate condition he said 
at the high school we didnt have a gymnasium we didnt have 
a cafeteria 
after integration was ordered all but nine white students left 
the 1300student district for private schools according to a 1971 
news story only two of the districts 60 teachers were white but 
whites held all but one seat on the school board 
now theres a brand new 1 million elementary school a 4 
million high school surrys per capita student spending is 5633 
nearly the highest in virginia 
and although the assembly sometimes criticizes the black 
superintendent he has been successful in working to bring at 
least 80 percent of the white children back hardy said 
the blackwhite ratio among students is now 73 percent to 27 
percent according to martha rollings assistant to the 
superintendent for instruction in the general population about 
six out of 10 people are black hardy said 
there are 58 black teachers 34 white three blacks and two 
whites sit on the school board 
improvement in standardized test scores has been dramatic for 
example surry eighth graders ranked in the eighth percentile 
nationally in reading in 1979 now theyre at the 49th within 
reach ms rollings said of the national average 50th 
percentile were working on it she added 
anderson knows the statistics and the faces they represent 
you dont have to think of symbolic changes he said you 
can transform a whole community 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

