<TEXT>
refugees fleeing occupied kuwait say 
resistance fighters are staging desperate and daring attacks 
including suicide bombings and that iraq has been unable to wipe 
them out 
in jordan escaping arabs said kuwaitis opposed to the iraqi 
annexation have been clashing with proiraqi palestinians in 
kuwait one refugee said dozens of people had been killed 
the small oilrich emirate was overrun by the powerful iraqi 
army on aug 2 and annexed six days later most communication with 
the outside world has gradually been cut by the invaders 
refugees arriving sunday at the saudi arabian border crossing of 
khafji said one kuwaiti resistance fighter mounted a suicide car 
bomb attack friday on an iraqi position at a hospital in the kuwait 
city suburb of jabriyeh 
the attack could not be independently confirmed but the 
clandestine kuwait radio also reported it saying an unspecified 
number of iraqi soldiers were killed or wounded 
in an apparent reference to the same incident the kuwaiti 
newspaper alanbaa now publishing in cairo said iraqi soldiers 
had been using the hospital as a headquarters 
a similar attack tuesday destroyed an iraqi checkpoint near the 
entrance to kuwaits harbor the refugees said 
some refugees said they witnessed a brief attack wednesday four 
kuwaiti men armed with rifles fired on an iraqi emplacement at the 
town of jeleeb alshuyoukh nine miles southwest of the capital 
the iraqis conterattacked with machine guns and a tank and the 
four resistance fighters took shelter in a nearby mosque the tank 
fired at least three shells into the mosque killing one of the 
attackers and injuring two the other fled according to the 
refugees 
one iraqi officer was sighted wednesday dangling by the neck 
from a crane in downtown kuwait the refugees said without 
elaborating 
most resistance attacks take place under cover of darkness the 
refugees said none could be independently confirmed 
the guerrillas who call their movement humane resistance 
have also set up an informal organization to handle matters like 
distribution of goods the refugees said 
british journalist victor mallet who was in kuwait at the time 
of the invasion said the resistance quickly developed into a 
guerrilla force mounting ambushes and sniper attacks often with 
weapons taken from police stations 
the kuwaiti armed forces numbering about 20000 were quickly 
overwhelmed by iraqs tankled assault 
mallet who eventuallly escaped across the desert to saudi 
arabia quoted a member of the deposed ruling alsabah family as 
saying that the resistance was developing an underground political 
and military structure and was in contact with the exiled goverment 
abroad 
the plan was to encourage popular defiance and demoralize 
iraqi troops already uncertain about their mission mallet who 
writes for the financial times reported last week from the the 
saudi capital riyadh 
one big problem for the resistance movement has been lack of 
coordination separate groups have formed in various parts of the 
country mallet said 
the resistance groups are also beset by logistical problems and 
lack of weaponry he said 
among the noncombat tasks being carried out by the resistance 
are care of the sick the distribution of food and fuel and 
guarding against profiteers the refugees here said in interviews 
egyptian refugee sameh alminyawi said his wife and daughter 
would travel on to egypt but that he himself would return to 
kuwait and join the resistance because this is my duty to the 
country where i lived and worked seven years 
i dont care what politicians may say or do but these nazis 
should be stopped at any cost he said of the iraqi invaders 
the refugees described streams of iraqis arriving in kuwait by 
car to buy televisions radios and other appliances kuwait is 
facing shortages of milk sugar rice and soap they said 
electric appliances which are scarce in iraq were being sold 
by iraqi troops who looted them from houses the refugees claimed 
they said iraqi officials appeared on kuwaiti television 
thursday with seven prisoners four syrians two egyptians and a 
kuwaiti and announced they would be executed for looting cash and 
gold from shops 
at the ruweishid border post in jordan arabs arriving from 
kuwait described nights shattered by gunfire as kuwaitis opposed to 
the iraqi annexation ought proiraqi palestinians 
kuwaitis are becoming very nervous and violent they shoot and 
kill other arab civilians for no reason said mohammad ahmad 
almaarouf a tunisian merchant 
he was one of thousands of arabs who flooded through the desert 
border post sunday as iraq tightened its grip on westerners in 
kuwait and iraq 
a senior jordanian security official speaking on condition of 
anonymity said iraqi authorities had notified jordans government 
that at least 350000 arabs will be crossing through ruweishid this 
week 
maarouf and other evacuees said the shootouts in kuwait followed 
violent political discussions 
mohammed ali an egyptian said iraqi troops were trying 
desperately to stop the shootouts that have left tens of 
palestinians dead 
