<TEXT>
this resort town nestled between pine forests 
and the st lawrence river has been turned into an armed camp and 
it may take a long time for the wounds to heal from the standoff 
between mohawks and police 
the lives of almost everyone here have been changed by the july 
11 shootout between mohawks from the adjacent kanesatake reserve 
and provincial police who stormed barricades set up by the indians 
one policeman was killed although it is unclear which side 
fired the fatal shot 
the mohawks were protesting the villages plan to expand its 
ninehole golf course onto land the indians claim contains a sacred 
burial ground 
villagers saw their peaceful existence explode that day 
property values have plummeted incomes have dropped and trust 
between mohawks and the mostly french canadian local residents has 
evaporated 
now this community of 1800 a summer tourist resort and 
retirement home for many in the montreal area has been turned 
into a police camp 
twothirds of the people have fled their homes either living 
with relatives or in hotels in the region while awaiting the 
outcome of negotiations between the mohawks and federal and 
provincial officials 
i think there will be longterm psychological effects 
said louis bricault a psychologist hired by the municipality to 
help residents deal with their problems 
they are suffering from feelings of anxiety unhappiness 
hostility impotence and defeat there are some people for whom 
these reactions have become very intense 
even when the crisis is over it is unlikely life can ever be 
the same 
we have to find a way to live together said yvan patry 
mayor of oka parish the larger community that surrounds both oka 
village and the kanesatake reserve 
patry said the problem must be solved because the mohawks are 
not going to leave oka and neither are the nonindians 
my greatest wish is that it returns to the way it was before 
we were here together before well be here together afterward 
the economic losses have yet to be calculated there are small 
