<TEXT>
richard l strout a washington journalist 
from the harding administration to ronald reagans first term in 
the white house has died at the age of 92 
he died sunday night at georgetown university medical center 
where he had been admitted after a bad fall on aug 8 said godfrey 
sperling strouts longtime colleague at the christian science 
monitor 
strout reported for the monitor for more than 60 years and wrote 
the political column trb from washington in the new republic 
from 1943 to 1983 he retired from the monitor in 1984 
in strouts hands the trb column became one of the most widely 
followed expressions of liberal political opinion in the nation 
when he gave it up the new republics editors observed you 
dont get out of strouts church without hearing the sermon but 
the hymns are lovely he looks and listens and tells you what 
he has seen and heard in vivid simple words 
in his first column at the height of world war ii strout 
called for a national statement of postwar aims saying when a 
man dies he wants to die for something important 
he described the eisenhower administration as government by 
sedative and likened redbaiting sen joseph r mccarthy rwis 
to a mist that carries lethal contagion 
of richard nixon then vice president he wrote in 1958 he is 
out for the kill and the scalp at any cost 
after his retirement his name remained on the magazines 
masthead as a contributing editor the trb column has been written 
in recent years by senior editor michael kinsley 
the column was written anonymously for years by kenneth 
crawford and others and then by strout more recently it has been 
signed the name trb was coined by bruce bliven an editor of the 
magazine before it moved from new york to washington bliven who 
carried copy to the office by subway said the initials stood for 
brooklyn rapid transit in reverse 
on his 80th birthday in 1978 strout still active at his job 
said if you live long enough people confuse ability with 
longevity im just an analytical writer with some color im not a 
whiz bang 
the same year he was given a special citation by the pulitzer 
prize committee for his lifetime achievement strout also won the 
george polk memorial award in 1958 and the national press clubs 
fourth estate award in 1975 among others 
strout was born in cohoes ny and raised in brooklyn his 
father was an english teacher who wrote poetry like him his 
parents both lived into their 90s 
after graduation from harvard in 1919 strout worked his way 
across the atlantic on a grain ship and worked for two years as a 
reporter and editor on the sheffield england independent after 
returning to the united states in 1921 he worked briefly as a 
reporter for the boston post he went to work for the bostonbased 
monitor in 1922 and transferred to its washington bureau in the 
early 1920s 
as a reporter for the newspaper he covered the teapot dome 
scandal presidential political conventions and campaigns the new 
deals efforts to deal with the depression the allied invasion of 
normandy on dday in 1944 and many other stories 
a collection of his columns trb views and perspectives on 
the presidency was published in 1979 in 1936 he and humorist 
eb white coauthored a book called farewell to the model t 
strout was a champion of the parliamentary system of government 
used in britain and canada he said the united states 
eighteenthcentury government with its presidential system 
was inflexible and resulted in long and drawnout presidential 
campaigns and anachronistic nominating conventions 
strout is survived by his wife the former ernestine wilke 
their two children elizabeth zimmerman of minneapolis and mary 
rubeiz of geneva switzerland and three children by a previous 
marriage alan mayne strout of weston mass phyllis norris of 
santa cruz calif and nancy dulaney of washington survivors also 
include 11 grandchildren and two great grandchildren strouts 
first wife edith mayne died in 1932 
a private funeral service is planned the family asked that 
memorial donations be made to all souls church unitarian of 
washington 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900820-0049 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
president bush today signed into law new 
federal and state logexport restrictions to help offset lost 
timber jobs and reduced harvests expected to result from protection 
of the rare northern spotted owl in the pacific northwest 
the new law is designed to bolster the timber supply for 
domestic timber processors it bans exports of unprocessed logs 
from most stateowned lands in the west 
the restrictions will have the biggest impact in washington 
oregon and northern california where dramatic timber harvest 
reductions are anticipated because of federally mandated protection 
of oldgrowth forests inhabited by the spotted owl 
the prohibitions are included in a trade bill bush signed today 
before giving a speech in baltimore a white house spokeswoman said 
about one in four logs currently cut in the northwest is shipped 
to more lucrative foreign markets 
under the new law washington will be allowed to continue to 
export 25 percent of its stateowned logs rawlog exports will be 
banned outright in oregon california idaho montana nevada 
wyoming utah colorado arizona and new mexico 
the export ban is expected to keep at home more than 600 million 
board feet of timber annually that currently is being exported 
that includes about 350 million board feet on washington state 
lands and 100 million board feet on oregon state lands 
the new law also makes permanent the prohibition on raw log 
exports from federal lands in the west and close loopholes in that 
ban those loopholes called direct and indirect substitution 
have enabled some timber companies to obtain federal logs from a 
third party for their domestic mills while shipping their own 
private logs overseas 
in each of the last two years about 36 billion board feet of 
unprocessed timber has been exported from washington and oregon 
about 80 percent of the total nationally 
a board foot is a piece of timber onefoot wide by onefoot long 
and one inch thick 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

