the 40minute flight showed that the pilots were not impaired by 
alcohol 
but assistant us attorney elizabeth de la vega questioned 
whether the pilots could have handled an emergency if one had 
developed 
the law does not require that we have to wait for a tragedy to 
happen before we find someone guilty she told the jury 
northwest fired the pilots for violating the companys 12hour 
prohibition against drinking before flying and the faa revoked 
their licenses the faa prohibits flying within eight hours of 
drinking and prohibits pilots from flying with bloodalcohol 
concentrations of 004 percent or more 
the trial opened july 25 and jurors got the case on thursday 
the federal law providing criminal penalties for operation of a 
common carrier while under the influence of alcohol or drugs was 
adopted in 1986 and amended in 1988 besides planes the law 
applies to commercial boats trains and passengercarrying buses 
prior to enactment of the law pilots were covered only by faa 
regulations there were no federal criminal penalties for flying 
while intoxicated 
the law states that an individual with a bloodalcohol content 
of 010 percent or more shall be presumed to be under the influence 
of alcohol but it does not state flatly that that percentage makes 
a person automatically guilty 
us district judge james rosenbaum told jurors that they had to 
decide whether a defendant is so affected by an alcoholic 
beverage that the person does not possess that clearness of 
intellect and control of himself as he otherwise would 
