<TEXT>
thousands of people with heart problems might 
no longer qualify for federal disability pay under a bush 
administration proposal to expand the use of a controversial 
exercise test 
sen john heinz rpa and new york state officials contend the 
tests which require pedaling a bicycle or walking on a treadmill 
could be unfairly used to exclude deserving applicants 
there can be no question that in this day of mammoth federal 
deficits even minimal savings are appreciated heinz said but 
to create savings by distorting congressional intent is 
unacceptable and a blatant disregard for the public interest 
the government estimates it will save 30 million in the plans 
first year and 220 million a year by 1995 plans for the testing 
program are still being finalized and would be subject to public 
comment 
the social security administration receives 195000 disability 
applications a year based on heart problems if the proposal went 
into effect the agency said cardiovascular benefits would drop as 
much as 5 percent and thousands of people would lose eligibility if 
the tests showed the applicants werent sufficiently disabled 
ssa already uses the procedure in many cases to gauge the 
severity of heart disorders but the proposed regulations would 
require a treadmill test for every disability benefit applicant 
with heart disease who could safely undergo one 
under the proposal applicants would qualify for social security 
disability payments averaging 560 a month only if the ailment is 
deemed serious enough to prevent them from working 
heinz ranking republican on the special committee on aging 
told ssa in a letter last month that the proposal violated 
individuals rights to have their cases fully heard 
new york attorney general robert abrams said in a prepared 
statement he was concerned that the federal government will 
continue to place predominant emphasis on the treadmill test in the 
face of other reliable medical evidence 
the test would be the primary though not exclusive basis 
for evaluating whether people with heart problems can work ssa 
commissioner gwendolyn king said in a february memorandum to health 
and human services secretary louis sullivan 
ssa wants the change despite a federal appeals court ruling in 
june that upheld a new york federal court ruling forbidding the 
agency from denying benefits based solely on the treadmill test 
when other evidence was available 
the 2nd us circuit court of appeals said the test often fails 
to detect one of the most common cardiovascular disorders known as 
ischemia evidence showed that the treadmill test resulted in 
misdiagnosis of ischemic heart disease more than onethird of the 
time the court said 
an individual who does not show signs of heart disease during 
a treadmill test may still be severely disabled from ischemia 
the court said false assessments may occur because treadmill 
testing does not consider the full range of stresses and exertions 
that arise at the workplace or in daily living 
more than 5 million americans have the disorder which accounts 
for 60 percent of all heart ailments and is characterized by 
narrowing of the arteries and chest pain 
the administration may ask the court to reconsider said ssa 
spokesman phil gambino 
we disagree with the courts decision because we believe that 
even currently we wont use the test in exclusion of other medical 
evidence gambino said in an interview last week 
people already receiving benefits would be affected only if a 
treadmill test demonstrated that their condition had improved since 
their initial claim 
</TEXT>
