<TEXT>
psychology pioneer bf skinner applied his 
theories of behavior modification to his own life a friend 
recalled monday as tributes poured in for the man who died last 
weekend 
skinner invented a reward system for himself to speed his 
learning of french grammar said ted blau he would study the verbs 
on an exercise treadmill and give himself a break when he got 
something right 
fred was never a man to let things go to waste said blau 
blau a clinical psychologist in tampa fla became friends with 
skinner after meeting him in 1973 
skinner the father of behavioral psychology and a professor 
emeritus at harvard university died saturday at mount auburn 
hospital in cambridge after battling leukemia he was 86 
his theories bore the cold clinical edge of laboratory tests 
but friends and colleagues remembered him as a warm and gentle man 
who believed that human beings are just another organism shaped by 
their environment 
critics say many of skinners ideas were inhumane but 
supporters point out that he left his mark on treatment methods to 
improve the lives of the mentally ill drug addicts and others 
his death elicited emotional responses from friends and 
supporters 
i was kind of teary all day yesterday said jack michael 
who teaches psychology at western michigan university its just 
kind of the end of a period that was important to all of us 
skinner experimented with pigeons and rats to show that systems 
of rewards and punishment could shape animal behavior he taught 
pigeons to play ping pong by reinforcing behavior patterns 
the practical application of skinners theories can be seen in 
popular programs to help people lose weight stop smoking and 
toilet train children 
skinner for many of us is a person of the same status who has 
the same impact on the understanding of behavior that darwin had in 
the area of biology or that newton had in the area of physics 
michael said 
charles darwin postulated the modern theory of evolution and 
sir isaac newton formulated the laws of gravity and motion 
fred keller 91 a psychologist retired from columbia 
university first met skinner in 1928 when they were graduate 
students at harvard 
i first thought he was just a brilliant student whom i 
liked said keller who lives in chapel hill nc 
he was widely read keller said he was clearly a highly 
intellectual and highly intelligent young man and that was 
apparent from the first i think all of his classmates at harvard 
recognized that he was an outstanding scientist 
william mckeachie professor of psychology at university of 
michigan said he exchanged many letters with skinner and sharply 
disagreed with his views 
but we were friends mckeachie said he asked me to review 
one of his last manuscripts 
skinners theories have had a major effect on education and the 
running of mental hospitals and prisons he said 
skinner developed token economies in which people in 
institutions could earn rewards by good behavior and meeting goals 
teachers learned to pay more attention to classroom techniques 
which could affect how students behave and learn 
skinner was honored one week ago for his lifetime of achievement 
by the american psychological association at their convention in 
boston 
he was nominated many times to be president of the apa but 
turned it down said blau a former apa president 
he did not believe that psychologists serious about their work 
should be distracted by political ins and outs 
