<TEXT>
richard l strout who reported on washington 
during 12 administrations and skewered the mighty as a liberal 
columnist has died he was 92 
strout died sunday night at georgetown university medical 
center godfrey sperling his longtime colleague at the christian 
science monitor said strout was hospitalized after an aug 8 fall 
strout reported for the monitor from 1922 to 1984 for the first 
couple of years at the newspapers home office in boston and then 
in its washington bureau he wrote about presidents from warren g 
harding to ronald reagan 
from 1943 to 1983 he wrote the political column trb from 
washington in the new republic magazine the column was also 
syndicated to newspapers 
as a columnist strout described the eisenhower administration 
as government by sedative likened sen joseph r mccarthy 
rwis to a mist that carries lethal contagion and said 
thenvice president richard nixon was out for the kill and the 
scalp at any cost 
as a reporter he covered presidential political campaigns and 
conventions the teapot dome scandal that rocked the harding 
administration franklin d roosevelt and his new deal and the 
dday invasion of normandy in 1944 
the trb column was written anonymously for years by kenneth 
crawford and others and then by strout it is currently written by 
michael kinsley a senior editor of the magazine and carries his 
byline 
when strout gave up the column the editors of the magazine 
wrote you dont get out of strouts church without hearing the 
sermon but the hymns are lovely he looks and listens and 
tells you what he has seen and heard in vivid simple words 
the columns name was coined by bruce bliven an editor of the 
new republic before it moved from new york to washington bliven 
carried copy to the office by subway and said the initials were 
those of the brooklyn rapid transit in reverse 
after strouts retirement his name remained on the magazines 
masthead as a contributing editor 
in 1978 strout was given a special citation by the pulitzer 
prize committee for his lifetime achievement strout also won the 
george polk memorial award in 1958 and the national press clubs 
fourth estate award in 1975 among others 
strout was born in cohoes ny and raised in brooklyn his 
father was an english teacher who wrote poetry his parents both 
lived into their 90s 
after graduating from harvard in 1919 he worked his way across 
the atlantic on a grain ship and served an apprenticeship as a 
reporter and copy editor for english newspapers after returning to 
the united states in 1921 he worked briefly as a reporter for the 
boston post before joining the monitor 
he was the author of trb views and perspectives on the 
presidency a collection of columns published in 1979 and 
coauthor with eb white of a booklength essay on the ford model 
t automobile published in 1936 
strout is survived by his wife ernestine their two children 
elizabeth zimmerman of minneapolis and mary rubeiz of geneva 
switzerland and three children from a previous marriage alan 
mayne strout of weston mass phyllis norris of santa cruz 
calif and nancy dulaney of washington survivors also include 11 
grandchildren and two greatgrandchildren strouts first wife 
edith mayne died in 1932 
a private funeral is planned 
</TEXT>
