at odds with president bush and half the 
arab world king hussein is persevering in his attempts to be a 
peacemaker in the persian gulf but his position is precarious 
since hussein assumed the throne in 1952 at age 16 he has 
managed to endure despite being at the vortex of the political 
upheavals that have plagued the middle east but his support for 
iraqs president following the aug 2 iraqi invasion of kuwait has 
left hussein vulnerable 
the crisis threatens jordans very social and political 
stability leading economist fahed fanek wrote in the 
englishlanguage jordan times newspaper on sunday 
the king has refused to join egypt syria and other arab states 
that have sent troops even if they are primarily token 
contingents to join the western buildup in saudi arabia against 
iraq 
hussein says he cannot participate if he is to pursue his 
efforts for a settlement within an arab context without outside 
intervention 
western diplomats in amman said hussein has shown a genuine 
desire to avert a potentially catastrophic military showdown in the 
gulf 
but if he joins the forces against iraqs president saddam 
hussein he risks the wrath of his powerful neighbor he also faces 
an internal threat jordans 3 million people have rallied behind 
saddam whom many arabs consider the only leader willing to stand 
up to israel and the united states 
more than 100000 jordanians have registered as volunteers to 
fight for iraq if war breaks out according to the jordanian 
committee for the support of iraq 
but if hussein supports the iraqi leader he is certain to face 
the jewish states military might and the revulsion of the 
international community 
dan shueftan a researcher at israels hebrew university said 
the king is walking between the devil and the deep blue sea 
another israeli ron benishai military commentator for the 
daily yediot ahronot justified husseins concern over israeli 
intentions 
theyre worried about a possible israeli preemptive strike 
he said 
jordan is saddams main avenue for confronting israel on the 
ground israels hardline government has warned it will attack if 
the iraqis enter jordan 
hussein has expressed discouragement over what he sees as the 
failure of the west especially the united states to get israel to 
the negotiating table 
he told jordanian newspaper editors over the weekend jordan 
will pursue its efforts with all its powers on the arab and 
international level to deescalate the gulf crisis 
bush said after meeting with hussein on thursday in 
kennebunkport maine that he had not come away with any feeling 
of hope that iraq will withdraw from kuwait despite intensifying 
international pressure 
the king painted an equally grim picture 
this is the most crucial stage ever in arab history he told 
the editors 
the arabs could either survive with a place under the sun 
among other nations or god forbid live in darkness losing 
everything they have he warned 
hussein has declared he still recognizes sheik jaber alahmed al 
sabah the emir of kuwait overthrown by saddams invasion he has 
said he will abide by the un economic sanctions imposed against 
iraq to force its withdrawal from kuwait 
but he has not implemented them jordans economy burdened with 
an 8 billion debt is heavily dependent on trade with iraq nearly 
all its oil comes from there 
jordans red sea port of aqaba remains baghdads economic 
lifeline 
the european community has discussed compensating jordan for 
joining the blockade of iraq 
but fanek the economist said all the compensation in the 
world would not make up for the farreaching economic and 
political losses jordan would suffer which threaten not only the 
national income but also national security 
</TEXT>
