with a second trial looming in the gang rape of 
a central park jogger a lawyer who was involved in previous 
racially charged cases joined the appeal monday of one of the young 
men already convicted 
the victim who recovered from nearfatal injuries she suffered 
during the gang rape and resumed her career as an investment 
banker said through intermediaries she wont comment on the 
weekend conviction of three youths 
a hearing was scheduled for sept 10 in state court on jury 
selection in the trial of the three other defendants kharey wise 
18 steven lopez 16 and kevin richardson 15 
the six are accused of being among a larger gang of blacks and 
hispanics that rampaged through the park the night of april 19 
1989 accosting and threatening joggers and others the white woman 
who has become known as the central park jogger was raped beaten 
with a brick and left for dead in a pool of blood and mud 
yusef salaam 16 antron mccray 16 and raymond santana 15 
were convicted saturday of rape assault robbery and riot but 
acquitted of attempted murder and sodomy 
they were immediately ordered jailed by justice thomas galligan 
they are to be sentenced sept 11 as juvenile offenders and face a 
maximum of up to 10 years in prison 
lawyers for all three have promised appeals 
and on monday the office of activist attorney c vernon mason 
announced that he would handle mccrays appeal 
mason represented victims in the howard beach trial in which 
three whites were convicted of manslaughter for their part in 
chasing a black man to his death on a highway in 1986 he also 
advised tawana brawley a black teenager whose claim she was raped 
by whites drew widespread attention but eventually was rejected by 
a grand jury 
masons legal secretary lenita jones also said that louis 
farrakhan leader of the nation of islam would take part in a 
nationwide support campaign 
the central park jogger whose name has been withheld by most 
media kept to herself in the aftermath of the verdict 
she has no comment as there are still other legal proceedings 
pending said lisa barowitz a spokeswoman for salomon brothers 
her employer 
assistant district attorney elizabeth lederer who prosecuted 
the case also refused to discuss the joggers reaction to the 
verdict i respect her privacy the prosecutor said 
the new york post quoted an unidentified source as reporting 
that the jogger said thank god this is over when she heard of 
the verdict 
she was thrilled she was relieved she was grateful to the 
jurors the source was quoted as saying she called them 
wonderful people 
wise lopez and richardson face 13 charges each including 
attempted murder rape robbery assault sodomy and riot 
lopez and richardson face the same penalties if convicted on the 
top counts up to 10 years in prison but wise because he was 16 
when the crime occurred can be punished as an adult and sentenced 
to up to 25 years 
the three teenagers signed written statements and gave 
videotaped statements to police and prosecutors as in the first 
trial the statements appear to be the prosecutions crucial 
evidence 
