foreign minister hansdietrich 
genscher proposed monday that the official granting of 
international approval to german unity be moved up a month to 
october 
current plans call for the results of talks on international 
aspects of german unification to be presented to a november meeting 
in paris of the 35nation conference on security and cooperation in 
europe csce 
member nations of the csce include the united states canada 
the soviet union and all european countries except for albania 
the four world war ii allies and the two germanys have reached 
basic agreement on how to iron out international complexities of 
german unity 
probably the greatest obstacle was moscows insistence that a 
united germany cannot be a nato member the soviets have since 
reversed their position in an agreement that will allow red army 
troops to remain in what is now east germany during a transition 
phase 
the six nations that were involved in those talks the united 
states britain france the soviet union and the two germanys 
are working on a final document that will cover the results of the 
negotiations 
genscher said monday that document should be presented to a 
meeting of csce foreign ministers in new york city on oct 12 
rather than at the paris gathering 
during the early stages of the sixnation talks it looked like 
german unity would not happen before the end of the year 
but the unification process has sped up quickly and the merger 
now looks likely to occur oct 14 at latest 
