<DOCNO> AP900820-0099 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
president bush signed a trade bill monday 
restricting state and federal log exports in an effort to save 
thousands of timber jobs affected by automation and federal 
protection of the northern spotted owl 
bush said there was no doubt that high levels of export of 
unprocessed timber have contributed to the decline in habitat 
that caused the northern spotted owl to be listed as threatened 
while i am supporting this provision because it assists in the 
preservation of critical habitat i also note that it will ease the 
economic transition in areas affected by the listing of the spotted 
owl bush said 
the log measure is intended to preserve the pacific northwests 
dwindling timber supply for domestic mills along with enough 
oldgrowth stands to save the northern spotted owl from extinction 
the bill makes permanent what had been a yeartoyear ban on the 
export of raw logs from federal land and imposes a new ban on state 
lands in california and oregon exports from stateowned land in 
washington would be reduced but not halted 
log exports from privately owned lands would still be allowed 
but the timber industry generally would be prohibited from 
substituting them for logs from federal lands as a way to escape 
the ban 
the legislation passed by congress earlier this month also 
permanently extends the dutyfree status of 4 billion in imports 
from 24 caribbean and central american nations including nicaragua 
and panama 
americas security and prosperity depend in large measure on 
continued progress toward democracy and economic development in the 
caribbean basin bush said in a written statement 
the legislation did not expand the trade benefits to cover 
imports of textiles shoes sugar and methanol commodities that 
could threaten us farmers and jobs it did however expand the 
program to give duty free status to articles processed in caribbean 
countries from us materials and to certain leather products 
president reagans 1983 caribbean basin initiative was intended 
to lift the regions depressed economy through direct aid and an 
elimination of tariffs and other trade barriers to spur 
exportoriented businesses 
critics say the initiative has failed to large degree because 
the direct governmenttogovernment aid fell victim to us budget 
deficits and drastically reduced imports of oil petroleum products 
and sugar from the region 
the log export prohibitions will have the biggest impact in 
washington oregon and northern california where dramatic harvest 
cutbacks are beginning to materialize in government plans for 
oldgrowth forests inhabited by the threatened owl 
our mills need the logs and oregon millworkers need the 
jobs said sen bob packwood rore who estimated the law will 
save 5000 to 7000 jobs in his state alone 
what weve done with this legislation is say we want to keep 
jobs at home instead of shipping them overseas said sen brock 
adams dwash 
the shift in us trade policy is due primarily to the plight of 
the owl said rep john miller rwash 
there are other factors but clearly the owl focused 
everybodys energy on this problem and the owl spurred the state 
delegations and the administration to look at all sorts of options 
for addressing the timber shortage at the mills he said in a 
telephone interview 
</TEXT>
