the government proposed 280000 in fines 
monday against united parcel service accusing the company of 
willfully violating federal safety laws requiring that jobrelated 
deaths and injuries be reported 
the occupational safety and health administration said the 
alleged violations took place at the companys watertown conn 
facility 
ups the nations largest package delivery company was cited 
for failing to notify osha about a jobrelated death and failing to 
record more than 100 other injuries and illnesses the company also 
failed to record the number of lost workdays caused by the 
injuries the agency said 
john flick a spokesman for the company based in greenwich 
conn said there would be no immediate comment because lawyers had 
not reviewed the allegations which were issued late in the day 
last april osha proposed a 625000 fine against ups for 
alleged record keeping violations that occurred at the companys 
uniondale ny office 
osha launched the watertown inspection after ups failed to 
notify the labor department that a worker had been killed by a 
moving vehicle while crossing a street the probe was widened to 
include a review of all accidents and workersafety problems at the 
facility 
ups also was cited for allegedly not giving workers in watertown 
training on how to handle spills or providing them with breathing 
equipment while they clean up spills 
willful violations are those committed with an intentional 
disregard of or plain indifference to federal job safety laws 
ups has 15 workdays to appeal the governments allegations to an 
independent review commission 
