<TEXT>
president bush crossed a critical line monday 
in finally describing americans and other foreigners trapped in 
iraq and kuwait as hostages 
it may mean he is closer to sending some of the troops now 
massing in saudi arabia into iraq in a rescue operation or even an 
outright attack on baghdad 
or bush merely may have been acknowledging the obvious 
he held off for more than two weeks emphasizing diplomacy and 
appeals to iraqs saddam hussein to observe international norms 
hours before the president spoke to the veterans of foreign wars in 
baltimore his spokesman had told reporters concerning the term 
we would not use that word 
the plight of the foreigners seemed to worsen through the 
weekend there were threats to use them as human shields placed 
in strategic locations to deter us attack 
a handful of americans managed last week to cross the border to 
freedom but evidently none from kuwait over the weekend 
thirtyfive removed from a hotel in baghdad have not resurfaced at 
least a dozen possibly 14 others were taken from two hotels in 
kuwait city destination not certain 
so bush revised the speech prepared for him for the vfw national 
convention to inject that there can be little doubt whatever 
these innocent people are called they are indeed hostages and 
he warned iraq and everyone else not to underestimate us resolve 
the president took that decisive step after meeting with brent 
scowcroft his assistant for national security and with deputy 
secretary of state lawrence eagleburger 
with the assertion bush could be trying to establish a legal 
justification for an attack although it was not immediately clear 
that the status of the americans had changed under international 
law 
the president also may be preparing the american public 
psychologically for the support he needs to escalate from economic 
pressure on iraq to combat with grave risk to the lives of us 
troops and bomber crews 
but above all bushs description of the americans as hostages 
helps him develop a rationale for using force to try to rescue 
innocent us citizens who by no stretch of the imagination could 
be considered combatants 
saddams quickly rejected proposal to free the foreigners in 
exchange for a us military pullout from the persian gulf region 
set political conditions for their freedom richard boucher a 
state department spokesman noted 
it dramatizes the circumstances under which these people are 
being held boucher said 
last friday in a subtle shift boucher said he did not want to 
speculate about whether the americans might be described as 
hostages and then over the weekend thomas pickering the us 
envoy to the united nations called them hostages a description 
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater challenged 
until the situation darkened us officials insisted reporters 
should not use the term 
state department spokeswoman margaret d tutwiler repeatedly 
stressed the americans were not being held at gunpoint they were 
not being mistreated and efforts were under way to secure their 
departure frompiraq and kuwait 
from the days of the 19th century barbary pirates the united 
states and its leaders have rallied to the aid of americans 
detained abroad against their will but the risk of allout war 
dictates trying diplomacy first 
president jimmy carter exhausted all available means after 
iranian fundamentalists overran the us embassy in tehran in 1979 
and seized the embassy staff and marine guards he tried a military 
rescue operation that failed in a desert north of the capital but 
never pulled the trigger to fire on tehran 
the american television audience in the meantime was bombarded 
nightly with the message that the united states itself was being 
held hostage ronald reagan campaigning against carter 
capitalized on the frustrating situation and won the white house in 
1980 
the 52 remaining american hostages finally were released through 
carter administration diplomacy but they were not liberated until 
reagans inaugural and after 444 days of miserable detention 
reagan in his two terms did not succeed in freeing a number of 
other americans held hostage in lebanon by proiranian factions 
secret us arms shipments to iran may have been instrumental in 
the release of a couple but the other americans remained captive 
and at least two were murdered 
now it is bushs turn to grapple with hostageholders 
the iraq crisis looms as his toughest political challenge 
declaring the americans in iraq and kuwait to be hostages may 
expose him to a fate similar to carters he runs the risk of being 
branded a failure if the 530 or so in iraq and 2500 in kuwait are 
not freed soon 
direct military action to liberate them or at least to punish 
iraq could help or hurt the president depending on the results 
his delay in calling them hostages minimized the political risk 
for a while but monday bush crossed that line to an uncertain 
outcome 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
editors note barry schweid is the aps chief diplomatic writer 
