<TEXT>
a courtroom became an arena of artistic debate 
monday over whether five sexually explicit photographs by robert 
mapplethorpe should be judged separately or as part of an entire 
175picture exhibit 
defense lawyers for the contemporary arts center and its 
director dennis barrie argued for dismissal of a misdemeanor 
charge of pandering obscenity he said the exhibition as a whole 
wasnt legally obscene 
both the director and the gallery were charged when they showed 
the photos by the late artist which previously had drawn the anger 
of us sen jesse helms and helped prompt congressional action to 
restrict funding of work deemed obscene 
in addition to that defense motion municipal judge david j 
albanese considered a prosecution request to consider just the five 
pictures identified in the indictment in judging whether obscenity 
laws were violated 
albanese did not rule on either request 
judith reisman a communications consultant who said she has 
studied sexually explicit photographs for the justice department 
and the american family association testified that individual 
photographs would have affected visitors 
defense lawyer h louis sirkin countered but i go in to see 
the exhibit as a whole dont i 
absolutely not absolutely not ms reisman said there 
are people who walked in and saw one picture and left 
martin friedman of the walker art center in minneapolis 
testified for the defense that every picture in the sixweek 
exhibit had to be considered as part of the entire show he noted 
that the contemporary arts centers contract to show the pictures 
required it to show all of them 
the whole purpose of an exhibition is to set up context 
friedman said an exhibition must be all the pictures you cant 
isolate some of the pictures and talk about the exhibition 
the judge took over the questioning at several points during the 
3hour hearing asking defense witnesses if sexually graphic 
pictures were required as part of a survey of the career of the 
late mapplethorpe 
the judge asked evan turner director of the cleveland museum of 
art is there some danger if the gallerys direction of the 
theme was just a vehicle for exhibiting erotic photographs for 
people who wanted to see erotic photographs 
i dont think any of the photographs in this exhibition fits 
that definition turner said 
the five photographs identified in one count of a twocount 
indictment against barrie and the gallery depict homoerotic acts 
they are difficult images but they are important to 
understanding the artists approach friedman said 
the judge earlier ordered barrie and the gallery to stand trial 
sept 24 on another charge of using children in material involving 
nudity one picture in the exhibition included a boy with his 
genitals exposed another showed a girl with her genitals exposed 
the charges of pandering obscenity and using children in 
material involving nudity each would carry a maximum penalty of six 
months in jail and a 1000 fine for barrie the gallery could be 
fined 5000 on each charge 
the mapplethorpe exhibition closed in cincinnati on may 26 it 
opened in boston on aug 2 provoking demonstrations for and 
against the institute for contemporary art which is displaying it 
authorities in boston have not filed criminal charges 
