a government program offering wild horses for 
adoption to citizens is becoming increasingly costly with no 
evidence that federal rangeland has benefited a congressional 
study said monday 
the interior departments adoptahorse program is aimed at 
removing wild horses from federal rangeland so that herds do not 
exceed what the land can support about 60000 wild horses have 
gone through the program over the last decade 
but the general accounting office the investigative agency of 
congress questioned in a report whether the program is needed 
range conditions have not demonstrably improved and the 
number of wild horses removed has exceeded the capacity of the 
program the gao said 
the study said the interior departments estimates on how many 
horses should be removed often is based on unreliable information 
as to what the rangeland is able to accommodate 
in some cases the bureau of land management has removed horses 
from ranges only to increase authorized livestock grazing by 
ranchers thereby negating any reduction in total forage 
consumption and potential for range improvement the study said 
at the same time the government continues to have problems in 
disposing of horses taken off the range the study said 
some horses remain at training facilities for as long as 19 
months when no more than two months are needed for the training 
driving up the cost of the program 
the gao said the government also may face a costly longterm 
commitment to providing sanctuaries for horses that are not 
adopted the cost of the first such sanctuary is now nearly 
900000 a year and other sanctuaries likely will be needed the 
study said 
the report noted that the wild horse program had been the focus 
of other problems in the past because of an inability to find homes 
for the horses 
between 1984 and 1988 the blm opened the program to largescale 
adopters resulting in abuse of the program and thousands of the 
horses being sold by adopters to slaughterhouses 
the feewaiver adoption program resulted in the abuse and 
commercial exploitation of thousands of wild horses contrary to 
blms legislative direction the gao said noting that the 
program was halted in 1988 after public and congressional outcries 
the gao cited no evidence of such practices continuing but it 
noted that the regulations allowing a waiver of fees for adoptions 
has not been rescinded 
the blm earlier this year proposed new rules aimed at preventing 
a single adopter from controlling large numbers of wild horses 
reducing the potential for profits and abuses under the program 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

