<TEXT>
the boundaries on what information american 
journalists in saudi arabia can relay home are in place to protect 
soldiers families and to ensure against tipping off the iraqis a 
pentagon official said aug 15 
one of the ground rules prevents journalists from disclosing the 
size of troop units or where they are located in the desert in the 
dispatches that are shared with the nations news media on a 
pool basis 
thats the kind of stuff the iraqis would love to know you 
might as well be giving them grid coordinates to set their 
artillery for said the official who is helping to handle the 
pool coverage from washington he asked to remain unidentified 
another restriction on the 15member pool of us journalists 
flown to saudi arabia by the pentagon prohibits them from 
identifying individual soldiers except commandlevel officers 
by name 
that rule is in place to protect the gis families in the united 
states the pentagon official said 
you have people who dont much care for the fact that were 
there in the first place and who want to strike back at a target 
he said 
allowing the journalists to report how many troops are gathering 
at a certain spot would be giving the enemy the potential enemy 
information that is better left unsaid at this point the 
official said 
photographers are not prevented from taking pictures of anything 
they see but a group of us military escorts control where 
the pool reporters and photographers are taken each day 
if they are taken to an object or a human being they are not 
being prevented from taking pictures of anything the official 
said 
a military official does a security review of the stories 
before they are dispatched to the reporters washington bureau 
then a pentagon official in washington gives it a final review 
before it is allowed to be distributed by wire services and to 
other news organizations 
