<TEXT>
older californians are spending less time 
in hospitals and undergoing fewer major surgeries according to a 
medicare review 
medicare patients 65 years and older are being moved out of 
hospitals and into nursing homes and home health care settings 
earlier and more frequently said jo ellen ross chief 
executive officer of california medical review inc a nonprofit 
organization that contracts with the federal government to monitor 
medicare services 
as a result more federal resources should be spent on health 
care outside hospitals she said 
the shift corresponds to a national trend toward lower 
hospitalization rates among the elderly but it can create 
financial strain for the elderly according to experts who note 
that medicare does not pay for much of the care provided in private 
homes or elsewhere 
about 32 million californians over 65 receive medicare 
coverage but many supplement the coverage by private insurance or 
outofpocket payments 
the number of california medicare recipients admitted to 
hospitals dropped about 45000 from 1987 to 1989 although the 
number of elderly people served by medicare during that period 
increased by nearly 110000 according to the report which was 
issued last month 
surgery rates dropped nearly 11 percent in the 12 months after 
doctors were required in april 1989 to get permission from cmri 
before performing a number of major surgical procedures the report 
said 
the changes have saved taxpayers 114 million 
some physicians complain that they have to fend off pressures 
from hospitals to discharge medicare patients because hospitals are 
paid a flat rate for certain types of care but ross said studies 
show that rarely occurs 
 
