<DOCNO> AP900820-0182 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
cockroaches might prefer to starve 
to death than scurry anywhere near powerful repellents that 
researchers hope can be used to build roachproof homes and 
businesses 
richard brenner has spent six years creating a deterrent to 
cockroaches as an entomologist for the us department of 
agricultures gainesville fla research lab 
he has worked with air vent inc of peoria heights to develop 
the repellents and a deadly new bait that someday might provide 
owners of infested homes and businesses a lethal onetwo punch for 
controlling the pesky insect 
theres no silver bullet to do the job of cockroach 
eradication brenner said no single solution will ever solve 
cockroach problems 
but were coming up with some things that will prevent 
infestation and eliminate the growing number of health problems 
weve linked to cockroaches 
the products resulted from a twoyear research project funded by 
air vent 
mike daniels national sales manager for air vent envisions 
putting the repellent in insulation and other construction 
materials 
and air vent is ready to market the bait as part of a new attic 
ventilation system designed with brenners help that is designed 
to drive roaches out of attics 
brenners research has determined that cockroaches often enter a 
home through roof vents and small openings the insects prefer 
warm moist dark environments to breed and find attics ideal 
because of the static air 
other ideas for the repellents include using them on cardboard 
boxes that carry food and attract roaches when they sit in 
warehouses and storerooms 
the repellents are five years from receiving epa approval for 
sale to the public brenner said but the attic ventilation system 
and bait could reach the marketplace within a year he said 
the investment may be worth the wait brenner estimates that 
15 billion is spent each year on pesticides to kill cockroaches 
another benefit of the research was brenners discovery that 
cockroaches are responsible for serious allergy problems 
his study found cockroaches produce allergens that affect an 
estimated 10 million to 14 million people he said the cockroach 
allergens are the second most common allergy causer among 
asthmatics 
we need to design more insectresistent structures and 
eliminate infestation by cockroaches brenner said thats why 
were excited about these products we are making some progress 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

