country intended to increase oil production with or without 
approval from the organization of petroleum exporting countries he 
had urged the 13nation cartel to hold an urgent meeting to discuss 
the situation 
but a brief statement issued by opec headquarters in vienna said 
a majority of members did not endorse the call 
since the proposal of saudi arabia to hold such a conference 
has not been able to secure the necessary support an 
extraordinary meeting of the opec conference will consequently 
not be held said the statement carried by opecna the groups 
news agency 
it said opec president sadek boussena the algerian oil 
minister would meet with some other ministers before the end of 
the month because of the situation in the oil market and to 
reflect the organizations serious concern it gave no details 
the algerian news agency aps quoted an unidentified source close 
to boussena as saying that three nations had joined saudi arabia 
and venezuela in supporting a special meeting it did not name the 
countries 
iranian oil minister gholamreza aqazadeh was quoted by the 
official islamic republic news agency as saying he opposed an 
immediate meeting because there was enough oil in storage in the 
industrialized world to make up for the loss 
saudi arabia which pumps about a quarter of the cartels oil 
has an opec quota of just under 54 million barrels a day 
while its production could be boosted by as much as 2 million 
barrels more a day analysts predicted venezuela could produce 
about 500000 more barrels above its current level of 2 million 
barrels to help fill the oil gap nigeria could add a few hundred 
thousand barrels to its opec quota of 16 million barrels analysts 
said 
the united arab emirates also has the capacity to lift 
production from its quota of 15 million barrels a day to 2 million 
barrels or more but bogin predicted it might be reluctant to do so 
the uae like kuwait was criticized earlier this year by 
iraqi president saddam hussein for producing more than its opec 
quota and helping drive down oil prices he claimed lower prices 
cost iraq 14 billion in oil revenues in the past year 
late last month in geneva opec ministers agreed to limit 
production to 225 million barrels a day to try to push crude 
prices up to the new benchmark of 21 a barrel by years end 
